Date: Wed 26 May 2004 [edited]
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <arodriguezm@SaludFMV.org>
Source: The New Vision, Uganda, Wed 26 May 2004 [edited]
<http://www.newvision.co.ug/D/8/13/362405>

Uganda: Ebola Fever Alert Throughout Northern Border Region
---------------------------------------------------
A team of health workers from the [Ugandan] Ministry of Health was
yesterday still monitoring the northern border districts following an Ebola
haemorrhagic fever outbreak in southern Sudan. The Minister of health,
Brig. Jim Muhwezi, yesterday said no victims were reported in any of the
areas which were placed on high alert on Mon 24 May 2004.
"We have dispatched a team of health workers to the region to monitor the
situation. Our team has concluded that there is no trace of Ebola
haemorrhagic fever in Uganda yet," Muhwezi said in an interview. He urged
Ugandans to stay calm, saying it was unlikely that Ebola would extend into
northern Uganda. Muhwezi said the Government would not take chances, adding
that they would do anything possible to protect the people in case of an
outbreak of the disease in the area.
The World Health Organisation on Fri 21 May 2004 confirmed a virus of the
Ebola family [the family _Filoviridae_] in Hai-Cuba, Yambio county in
Western Equatorial Province of the Sudan. 4 people had died and 11 [5 and
20 as of Wed 26 May 2004] contracted the disease while 102, who made
contact with patients, were being monitored.
Muhwezi cautioned the people of northern Uganda against crossing into
Sudan. He told them to be careful while in contact with people from the
Sudan, saying any one in contact with an infected person risked getting the
disease. The area of the disease outbreak is more than 300 km northwest of
Uganda's northwestern border.
