[3]
Date: Thu 27 May 2004
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <arodriguezm@SaludFMV.org>
Source: East African Standard, Kenya, Thu 27 May 2004 [edited]
<http://www.eastandard.net/headlines/news27050411.htm>

Kenya: Border Controls Proposed to Prevent Introduction of Ebola
----------------------------------------------------
Medical experts want strict measures enacted to prevent the spread of the
deadly Ebola into Kenya. The experts made their recommendations on Tue 25
May 2004 following confirmation by the World Health Organisation that Ebola
had killed 5 people in southern Sudan.
The team from the Ministry of Health met under the aegis of the Disease
Outbreak Management Unit. Sources said the team, headed by Deputy Director
of Medical Services Dr F M Kamau, recommends that the government screens
visitors entering Kenya from the Sudan. And the Kenya Medical Association
has also told the government to move swiftly to stop the disease from
spreading into Kenya. The chairman, Dr Stephen Ochiel, asked the government
to act swiftly to ensure all visitors and relief workers are screened
before being allowed into Kenya.
Kenya shares a common border with Sudan, with major cross-border activities
taking place in Lokichoggio town in Turkana District, which is the nerve
centre of relief agencies working in southern Sudan. Several airlines
operate flights to Lokichoggio from Jomo Kenyatta International Airport,
but regular and frequent flights are to and from Wilson Airport.
It has also emerged that Kenyan researchers were among top world experts
working in southern Sudan's Equatorial Province to contain the virus, which
has so far infected 19 people. The Director of the Kenya Medical Research
Institute (Kemri), Dr Davy Koech, confirmed Kenyan experts flew into Sudan
last week after WHO expressed fear of an Ebola outbreak. Blood samples and
fluids from victims were then flown to Kemri's headquarters in Nairobi,
where the Ebola virus was confirmed. Also involved in the tests was the
United States Centre for Disease Control and Prevention.
WHO confirmed the Ebola infections on Mon 24 May 2004, but it said there is
no need yet to impose quarantine in the affected Yambio County. The head of
WHO's southern Sudan office, Dr Abdullahi Ahmed, told the East African
Standard yesterday that owing to the highly infectious nature of the
disease, all Sudan's neighbours, including Kenya, have been notified. Kenya
suffered a major Ebola scare in 2000, when an outbreak was reported in
Uganda. At that time, the government imposed screening rules for all
visitors entering Kenya from Uganda.
